fields.page_description: An incredible architectural experience of The Tower of Bethlehem, and The Jerónimos Monastery, the objects of UNESCO World Heritage Site. An opportunity to see Portugal's rich maritime heritage and cultural treasures.
fields.name: Belém’s Walking Tour
fields.why_title: Why Book Belem's Walking Tour With One Day Tours
fields.why_subtitle: Explore the stunning beauty of Portugal with our unforgettable experiences. Make a journey through history and times begin.
fields.info_subtitle: Enjoy a lovely walking tour in one of the most incredible areas in Lisbon – Belém, the significant landmark of the Age of Discoveries.
fields.short_description: An incredible architectural experience of The Tower of Bethlehem, and The Jerónimos Monastery, the objects of UNESCO World Heritage Site. An opportunity to see Portugal's rich maritime heritage and cultural treasures.
fields.full_description: We invite you to join this experience to see incredible architectural structures from the 16th century that have earned the status of UNESCO World Heritage Site – The Tower of Bethlehem, and The Monastery of Saint Jerome! But the list of historical treasures is not limited by that, as Belem is keeping a lot of other significant structures, the creation of which is dated back to the International Exhibit of 1940

fields.page_description: An exciting journey to the religious core of Portugal together with an architectural exploration of the Batalha Monastery, and the natural gem of Nazare. A short walk through medieval Obidos is one more accent for an unforgettable trip.
fields.name: Fátima + Batalha + Nazaré + Óbidos Group Tour
fields.why_title: Why Book A Full-Day Experience to Fátima, Batalha, Nazaré & Óbidos With One Day Tours
fields.why_subtitle: Explore the stunning beauty of Portugal with our unforgettable experiences. Make a journey through history and times begin.
fields.info_subtitle: The historical and religious experience, full of divines and revelations, mixed with intense cultural heritage
fields.short_description: An exciting journey to the religious core of Portugal together with an architectural exploration of the Batalha Monastery, and the natural gem of Nazare. A short walk through medieval Obidos is one more accent for an unforgettable trip.
fields.full_description: You will get the chance to visit Fatima, the religious core of Portugal. Additionally, the experience includes the exploration of Portuguese architecture with the Monastery of Batalha, being declared a UNESCO World Heritage Object. For an unforgettable lunch, we’ll stop in Portuguese Nazareth, home to the biggest waves, and the best surfing spot all over the World. At the end of the trip, we’ll make a short walk through Obidos, the most well-preserved medieval town in Portugal.

fields.why_subtitle: Explore the stunning beauty of Portugal with our unforgettable experiences. Make a journey through history and times begin.

fields.info_subtitle: Perfect experience to get acquainted with the cultural and architectural landmarks of an ancient Portuguese city
fields.short_description: The historical trip to Evora, the capital of Alentejo. Experience the timeless beauty of this captivating city, where Roman architecture, expressed in the Evora Cathedral, is tightly connected with modern influence.
fields.full_description: We invite you to spend an unforgettable day in the capital of Alentejo – Evora. Since the roman era this city has been one of the most important in Portugal.  First of all, we’ll see the roman temple that is safely kept till our times. We’ll witness examples of Portuguese architecture in all its authentic beauty, such as the Palace of King Manuel, Evora’s Cathedral, and Saint Francis Church of Evora.

fields.name_stop: Custard Tarts + Palace of Bethlehem + National Coach Museum
fields.description: Our next stop is tightly connected with the most famous Portuguese culinary treasures. We will have a chance to try “Pastéis de Belém” – the original Custard tarts in Portugal! Afterward, we'll go to the Palace of Bethlehem, the official residence of the Portuguese president, and the most visited museum per year in Por
Now it's time to walk to the picturesque riverside to see the Monument to the Discoveries, the monument added to the international exhibit of 1940.
Finally, to conclude our trip let's have a quick walk by Bethlehem marina on our way to the Tower of Belem, another brilliant piece of architecture from the 16th century, protected by UNESCO.

fields.name: Lisbon Oceanarium
fields.page_description: Lisbon Aquarium showcases diverse marine life in all its beauty, including a unique species. The huge central tank with sharks, rays, and other fascinating creatures is the main attraction.
fields.introduction_title: Lisbon Oceanarium: The Biggest in Europe
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The Oceanarium in Lisbon, built in 1998, is one of the largest in the world, displaying more than 25 thousand marine life species. This place is perfect for an exciting family visit, and will certainly appeal not only to children but also to all adults who are not indifferent to the beauty and uniqueness of the underwater world. Lisbon Oceanarium is unique because it contains the inhabitants of all oceans without exception in one place. There is also a second building connected to the main one by a transparent gallery. The place is open not only to conduct excursions here but also to carry out serious scientific research on underwater flora and fauna.

On the ground floor, there are 25 aquariums where you can view marine inhabitants individually. And in the center of the second floor, there is a huge tank about seven meters deep. Even though the representatives of different climatic zones are separated by a transparent partition, it is almost imperceptible, which emphasizes the idea of the unity of the waters of the World Ocean. This floor is also occupied by four thematic aquariums - in each of them is recreated the flora and fauna of one of the oceans. The second building is educational, as it hosts exhibitions, events, and excursions dedicated to the protection and safety of species.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The huge sunfish is the main attraction of the Oceanarium since its maintenance requires strict conditions. Also in the Lisbon Oceanarium lives a giant Pacific octopus weighing about 250 kg and with a tentacle span of 9 meters.

The collection includes endangered species such as seahorses, octopuses, manta rays, and mobulas. The entire population is strictly protected by a research team that cares about the health and living conditions of the inhabitants. In the outdoor pools, you can meet vices and parrots, penguins, and otters.

The main focus of the activities held here are organized excursions, but the base also regularly hosts master classes, exhibitions, concerts, and shows. The main purpose of most exhibitions is scientific and social activities, within which one can learn about endangered species of animals and the impact of human activities on the ecology of the seas. Some events are purely entertaining. In addition, it is possible to organize events upon individual request.
fields.short_introduction_text: Lisbon Aquarium showcases diverse marine life in all its beauty, including a unique species. The huge central tank with sharks, rays, and other fascinating creatures is the main attraction.
fields.info_subtitle: Lisbon Oceanarium is the door to a world of 8,000 marine inhabitants, highlighting the wonder and majesty of the marine life

fields.name: St. George's Castle
fields.page_description: The Castle of St. George is the heart of the Portuguese capital, the history of which began at the turn of two eras. In 1147, it was liberated by the Crusaders from the Moors. Afonso Henriques, the commander of the Crusaders, became the first ruler of the
fields.introduction_title: St. George's Castle in Lisbon: An Object of Lisbon Cultural Heritage and Notable Attraction
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The Castle of St. George is the heart of the Portuguese capital, the history of which began at the turn of two eras. In 1147, it was liberated by the Crusaders from the Moors. Afonso Henriques, the commander of the Crusaders, became the first ruler of the country. Then, until the 16th century, the castle was the official royal residence.

Outstanding architecture and history made the castle one of the symbols of the country, a great introduction to medieval history for tourists. The complex is memorable for its calm atmosphere and solemnity, perfect for the Lisbon city walking tour. It mesmerizes with gorgeous panoramic views of Lisbon with red-tiled roofs and the Tagus River. As for the collection of cannons and an archaeological museum, it's more than impressive.

From the top of the hill, there are open views of the ancient part of the city and houses with tiled roofs. The monument to the first king Afonso, who holds a shield and sword in his hands, is also located here. The castle went through numerous buildings and changed many times, the last time it was restored in the 20th century.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The fortress is presented not just by one castle, but by an ancient town, a popular destination for day tours from Lisbon. Visitors can see preserved fragments of medieval battlements, walking through the inner parks of olive trees of this magnificent landmark of Portugal. When Vasco da Gama returned from sea voyages, the celebration was here, as well as various significant events for the kingdom. The towers are open for visitors, so everyone has the opportunity to climb and take a walk along the fortress walls. 

For a more interactive experience, it's recommended to pay attention to the numerous multimedia exhibitions, held here every day. The Castle of St. George in Lisbon suffered badly from an earthquake in the 16th and 18th centuries. However, the fortress walls have been restored and are in good condition. In the Tower of Odysseus, for example, you can see panoramas of Lisbon, and an archaeological museum is located in one of the old wings of the fortress. Projected images on the walls show the major city's historical events, such as a simulated earthquake, the return of Vasco da Gama, the fall of the Church of Carmo, and much more, from the era of the Inquisition to the period of the Salazar dictatorship.
fields.short_introduction_text: Discover a stunning palace, a significant architectural and historical spot, one of the must-see things in Portugal. St. George's Castle is a great example of late Baroque architecture with typical decorations.
fields.info_subtitle: The Fortress of St. George is one of the main ancient landmarks in Lisbon and a top must-see spot

fields.name: Tram 28
fields.page_description: The iconic yellow tram route is a visiting card of the city. It goes through the historic districts of Lisbon, offering a charming and nostalgic journey through picturesque neighborhoods that showcase Lisbon's daily life.
fields.introduction_title: Lisbon's Iconic Tram 28: The Authentic Lisbon Tram Experience and Key Stops on the Route
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The yellow tram with the number 28 has become a symbol of the city and an interesting journey for Lisbon tours through the streets of the old city. It can be seen on postcards and leaflets as a well-known and charming attraction in Portugal, the same as Sintra castle or Nazare waves. The trip is fun for all categories of tourists, but it should be noted that it's not only touristic but also an active transport route for locals, so it can be quite busy.

The length of the route is 7 kilometers, and the journey takes from 40 to 60 minutes. For almost a century now, this tram has been tightly connected with the streets of Lisbon, perfectly fitting into the urban landscape and being its significant feature. The last modernization of the tram took place in the mid-90s. The emphasis was on the technical part, and the appearance is still as close as possible to the original.

If you want to take a seat, the best place for the beginning of tram route No. 28 is Martim Moniz Square. The route has existed for more than a century, during which it has remained virtually unchanged. The carriages are equipped with wooden seats.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
To inform the driver about a stop, simply pull the rope in the cabin. In some parts of the route, the streets are so narrow that passengers can reach out and touch the walls of houses.

As for the route itself, it's the main reason for the popularity of this tram among tourists and an answer to why many visitors choose this option instead of the Lisbon bus tour. For one ride, you can see the most significant spots in Lisbon. In general, the route is a funny experience that should be included in Lisbon tours. Starting from Martim Moniz Square, Lisbon's scenic tram journey passes through the Mouraria quarter, the historic Tram 28 route passes through the Alfama quarter, the Temple of Santa Engracia, the Cathedral of Sé, the Lisbon Cathedral, the Castle of St. George, the Santa Luzia observation deck, Plaza Commerce with the Arc de Triomphe, the Parliament Building, Baisha, Camoens Square, Santa Justa Elevator, Chiado, and Estrela Basilica. 

You should note that it's possible to get off at any stop, walk, look around and enjoy the city, and then get on the next one. Since there is only one railway track, the tram does not run often, approximately every 45–50 minutes. The last station, Campo de Ourique, is outside of Lisbon's historic center, so either jump off early or plan a return trip along the same route. Or walk back on foot, as walking around Lisbon is a pleasure!
fields.short_introduction_text: The iconic yellow tram route is a visiting card of the city. It goes through the historic districts of Lisbon, offering a charming and nostalgic journey through picturesque neighborhoods that showcase Lisbon's daily life.
fields.info_subtitle: Lisbon Tram 28 is the way to immerse yourself in the nostalgic past of Lisbon's historical streets and one of the must-see things in Lisbon

fields.name: Jerónimos Monastery
fields.page_description: Jerónimos Monastery, opened in 1495, is one of the most significant places in Lisbon, a sign of the era of prosperity of Portugal during the Age of Discovery, and a must-see place in the Lisbon city walking tour.
fields.introduction_title: Jerónimos Monastery: UNESCO World Heritage Object in Lisbon
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Jerónimos Monastery, opened in 1495, is one of the most significant places in Lisbon, a sign of the era of prosperity of Portugal during the Age of Discovery, and a must-see place in the Lisbon city walking tour. The facade of the monastery, made of soft beige sandstone, looks luxurious against the backdrop of spacious green gardens. In the west wing of the monastery is the Maritime Museum with Vasco da Gama Resting Place and the National Archaeological Museum of Portugal, making it a great choice for a full-day excursion. 

The first floor of the monastery is impressive with its luxurious, well-kept interiors. The specific feature on the second floor is a unique carving, elegant and sophisticated. Today the monastery is a big museum, but also it's used for the state purposes of the country and the world. The famous Treaty of Lisbon was signed here. 

All the parts of the monastery are unique, some of the columns show sea knots, sea monsters, corals, and many other marine motifs. That's why this attraction is always in the top places to visit for day trips from Lisbon. The greatest masters of stone carving expressed their art, creating one of Lisbon's architectural wonders, capturing scenes from the life of St. Jerome and the coat of arms of the king.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
A sculpture of Henry the Navigator, holding a sword in his hands, is located near the middle column, and stone lions are fighting at his feet. Archangel Gabriel, who is the guardian of Portugal, crowns the top of the portal. Today, the monastery is one of the major attractions of Portugal.

The Church of Santa Maria, located here, is an architectural masterpiece and a must-see place in the list of Belem district attractions. The church, with its genuine architectural style, can be called the heart of the Jeronimos Monastery. It amazes with its rich decor, soft light emanating from narrow lancet stained-glass windows, twisted columns reminiscent of scaffolding, a mesh vault, an abundance of bas-reliefs, and statues of saints and apostles in niches.

A visit to the Maritime Museum as a part of Lisbon tours will give both adult and young visitors an unforgettable experience as every exhibit seems to be imbued with the sea breeze and adventure. At the National Archaeological Museum, visitors will see the remains of the great events. The abundance of decorative elements in every corner of the monastery complex is impressive.
fields.short_introduction_text: Jerónimos Monastery, opened in 1495, is one of the most significant places in Lisbon, a sign of the era of prosperity of Portugal during the Age of Discovery, and a must-see place in the Lisbon city walking tour.
fields.info_subtitle: Lisbon Jerónimos Monastery is the national shrine of Portugal and one of the most beautiful Lisbon cultural landmarks of the Middle Ages

fields.name: Alfama District
fields.page_description: Alfama is a colorful mix of narrow streets, authentic houses, and Fado music in the air. The oldest district in Lisbon, it has its own unique historical charm with breathtaking views of the city.
fields.introduction_title: Lisbon's Historic Alfama District: Alfama Lisbon Travel Tips and Things to Do in Lisbon
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The Alfama district can easily be called the “soul” of Lisbon, as it's the most colorful, unique, and popular area of the Portuguese capital, and one of the spots for the Lisbon city walking tour. Alfama was the only area that survived the earthquake in 1755 and preserved its medieval spirit to this day. The entire area is located on rocky hills and consists of small narrow streets, along which you can walk endlessly. It belongs to the old part of the city, so within its borders are located the largest number of must-see attractions. Walking through this area, immerse yourself in the fascinating history of the old city, and pay special attention to such Alfama Lisbon attractions:

Se Cathedral is an iconic Lisbon symbol built on the site of an old Moorish mosque, which resembles an enemy fortress with massive towers. The building is well-kept from the Middle Ages, allowing one to appreciate the mystery of the Gothic style.

The National Museum of Azulejos is one of the most notable features of Lisbon. Small decorative clay tiles are on almost every building in the city center. The Azulejo Museum is the best idea for day trips from Lisbon to know the history of art and creation
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The Fortress of St. George is the surviving wall of an ancient defensive structure. It is located on the top of a hill, so you can enjoy not only the beauty of the ancient building but also the incomparable view of the city.

National Pantheon of Santa Engracia. It's one of the visit cards of Alfama, as its huge snow-white dome tower is visible from many points. 

Monastery of San Vicente de Fora is a significant religious attraction, and picturesque site in the area, harmoniously blending into the panorama of the city.

The area presents a wide range of observation platforms, which are considered the best Alfama Lisbon photography spots. The most interesting of them are Miradouro de Santa Luzia, Miradouro Sophia de Mello Breyner Andresen, Miradouro das Portas do Sol Observation Deck, and many others. You may find a lot of things to visit in Lisbon in other places, but in Alfama they are especially magnificent.

The Alfama district will create an unforgettable impression of Portugal's historical sites.  In the evening, you can hear the sounds of romances throughout the area, as the best singers perform in cafes and restaurants, where it is highly advisable to spend time with a glass of local wine
fields.short_introduction_text: Alfama is a colorful mix of narrow streets, authentic houses, and Fado music in the air. The oldest district in Lisbon, it has its own unique historical charm with breathtaking views of the city.

fields.name: Praca do Comercio
fields.page_description: Praca do Comercio, founded in the 15th century, is the place where Lisbon's development, connected with the time of great geographical discoveries, started.
fields.introduction_title: Visit Praca do Comercio: One of the Most Significant Lisbon's Landmarks
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Praca do Comercio, founded in the 15th century, is the place where Lisbon's development, connected with the time of great geographical discoveries, started. The first name, Palace Square, is connected with the first building on it, the royal palace of Ribeira. Then was an international maritime trade stage, when a port appeared, a shipyard, India House, and other administrative buildings along the river. However, the proximity to the water during the earthquake ruined Palace Square.

Nowadays, in the center of the square stands an equestrian statue of the Portuguese King Jose I, who was the head of the country during these troubled times and restored the city from scratch.

The Arc de Triomphe serves as a kind of gateway to the square. By the way, there is an excellent observation deck on it, where you can climb and look down on the Trade Square when you go on the Lisbon city walking tour. During various city events, a stage, screens, and tents are installed here, and the square has become one of the busiest Portuguese plazas in the city. By the way, on weekdays there are very few people here although it may seem so because of its enormous size. On weekends, Commerce Square hosts all sorts of events, including street performers.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
Evidence of the fact that there was once a royal palace is a pair of symmetrical houses near the water, the design of which is very reminiscent of the towers of a ruined castle. One of them now houses the Lisbon Museum. Another echo from palace times and Lisbon's cultural heritage is the marble staircase flanked by two columns (Cais das Colunas). According to one version, the staircase existed before the earthquake and led directly to the palace. For many years, it served to receive important guests, including Queen Elizabeth II of England. Well, now this is a favorite place for locals and tourists to watch the sunset.

The square opens up a panoramic view of the Tagus River and a breathtaking view of the 25th of April Bridge. It is one of the most beautiful tourist spots in Lisbon, especially at sunset. In terms of day trips from Lisbon, stroll along the 18th-century houses and the promenade, visit the Arc de Triomphe viewpoint, and listen to street musicians perform. It's highly recommended to try the national dishes of Portugal at Martinho da Arcada, one of the oldest restaurants in Lisbon, located here. You can also use a ferry to enter Lisbon through the Palace Square, as kings and queens did, by sailing to the pier by the Tagus River.

fields.name: Belem Tower
fields.page_description: One of the most beautiful symbols of Lisbon is the Belém Tower. The majestic structure stands right next to the water, creating an incredibly picturesque view of the historical part of the city - Belem.
fields.introduction_title: Belem Tower in Lisbon: Discover Belem Tower UNESCO Site and Cultural Heritage
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
One of the most beautiful symbols of Lisbon is the Belém Tower. The majestic structure stands right next to the water, creating an incredibly picturesque view of the historical part of the city - Belem.

The tower is one of the most popular landmarks in Portugal. At the end of the 80s, it was declared a cultural heritage monument, included in the UNESCO lists, and is under its protection. This point is one of the most significant spots for Lisbon city walking tour. The construction of the tower was carried out in 1514-1519 and is associated with the Age of Discovery, in which Portugal and Lisbon itself played one of the leading roles.

Since 1515, the tower has welcomed Lisbon sailors returning to their hometown with Venetian arcades, an abundance of architectural decoration, and a statue of Our Lady of Prosperous Returns, the patroness of Portuguese sailors since the time of Vasco da Gama. It’s worth coming here to admire the amazing architecture, see the collection of ancient cannons in casemates, see unusual sculptures of rhinoceroses, and enjoy the views of the river.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The Belem Tower architecture is unique, as it is massive and at the same time elegant structure, consisting of the observation tower itself and a powerful bastion at its foot, jutting into the natural harbor at the entrance to the city. As you approach the tower on your day trips from Lisbon, whether from the city or along the river, you will gradually discover all its amazing details. The architectural style in which this structure is made is called Manueline, which became widespread exclusively in Portugal, during its heyday as a maritime power. This style includes elements of Gothic, Renaissance, Moorish, and even a little Indian style. Basically, everything that the Portuguese were able to see thanks to their numerous expeditions. A true master, Francisco de Arruda, is the author of this magnificent architecture. 

The fortress consists of two parts: a five-story tower with statues of St. Michael and St. Vincent, equipped with a stunning Templar chapel, which is located inside, and a hexagonal bastion with 17 cannons. On the ground floor of the tower (bastion level). While going on Lisbon tours, it is worth exploring the open terrace from which the monarch himself once greeted returning travelers. Here is a statue of the Virgin Mary of Safe Returns, and the perimeter of the terrace is decorated with Moorish turrets reminiscent of exotic headdresses.
fields.short_introduction_text: One of the most beautiful symbols of Lisbon is the Belém Tower. The majestic structure stands right next to the water, creating an incredibly picturesque view of the historical part of the city - Belem.
fields.info_subtitle: Belem Tower is one of the most significant things to visit in Lisbon, located right on the seashore

fields.name: Azulejo Museum
fields.page_description: Azulejos are clay tiles, painted and covered with glaze, considered to be a traditional decorative material in Portugal and Spain. It came to Spain from Arab countries in the 15th century.
fields.introduction_title: National Azulejo Museum: One of the Most Colorful Lisbon Cultural Attractions
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Azulejos are clay tiles, painted and covered with glaze, considered to be a traditional decorative material in Portugal and Spain. It came to Spain from Arab countries in the 15th century. 

Traditionally, the tiles were colorful, but when the fashion for Dutch tiles spread across Europe in the 17th century, the azulejos also changed and still remain more often two-color white and blue. 

Azulejos can still be seen in the oldest monasteries in the country. Many eastern countries also use them, and if you have ever seen mosques lined with beautiful brightly painted glazed tiles, then this is the prototype of azulejos.

Traditional Portuguese azulejos are kept in the museum, located in the historical building of the Monastery of the Mother of God (Mosteiro da Madre de Deus), a perfect destination in terms of walking tours in Lisbon, Portugal. 

An old 16th-century monastery has an interesting history, because, in addition to the function of the monastery, it also became a place where you can see unique tile paintings from antiquity to modern times, brought from different countries.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The museum allows the visitor to contemplate a diverse collection of tiles, with products from different eras dating back more than 500 years to the present day. The museum itself is divided into several halls, visiting each of them you can understand the history and stages of development of this ancient art form.

The building also has majestic decoration, with most of the walls covered in hundreds of azulejos. The visitor can also see the Igreja Madre de Dues church through the glass, as shown in the photo. The decoration of gilded wood carvings is impressive.

This is perhaps one of Lisbon's lesser-known museums, and because it is located further from the historical center, outside the Baisha-Chiado area, it is often missed by tourists passing through Lisbon. 

But it is undoubtedly one of the most important museums in Portugal and is worth a visit anyway. This is an excellent program for day trips from Lisbon for the whole family and a unique place to feel the atmosphere of that time and see it through the eyes of a master.

Today, the Church of Madre de Deus is an integral part of the National Tile Museum, an important repository of the memory of Portuguese culture, and a notable place in the list of things to visit in Lisbon. The location is a perfect choice for everybody who is looking for a non-standard tourist program. 

The museum keeps an extensive collection that explains how tiles are made, their history, trends, and other important aspects related to this decorative and symbolic element.

fields.info_subtitle: Azulejo historic tile exhibits authentic craft tiles, showing the history of Portuguese art in all its prosperity

fields.page_description: One of the must-visit places for a Lisbon city walking tour is the Miradouro da Senhora do Monte observation deck. It may be a challenge to get there on foot, but it’s worth it as the breathtaking views over the city are guaranteed.
fields.introduction_title: Senhora do Monte Viewpoint in Lisbon: Top Spot for the Scenic Views of the City
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
One of the must-visit places for a Lisbon city walking tour is the Miradouro da Senhora do Monte observation deck. It may be a challenge to get there on foot, but it’s worth it as the breathtaking views over the city are guaranteed. 

The viewpoint is one of the places where the visitors can look from above at the tiled roofs and architecture of the buildings and feel like they’ve traveled 100 years back. The entire old city is spread out in front with a panorama of such popular attractions, as the Sao Jorge Castle, the Statue of Christ, the 25th of April Bridge, the Santa Justa ski lift, and the Carmo Monastery.

The easiest way to come here is on foot from the Intendente metro station. Although the path may seem a little steep, the panorama is worth every step.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
Miradouro da Senhora do Monte is one of the most popular spots to enjoy the best Lisbon panoramas and the tranquility, feeling the atmosphere of the old city. The viewpoint, surrounded by beautiful trees and cozy benches, is an easy escape from the crowds and noise of the big city. This is the perfect place for a romantic sunset with your nearest and dearest, or relaxation after exploring the city.

One more famous attraction, located here, is the chapel of Nossa Senhora do Monte. The visitors shouldn’t miss the opportunity to see one of the most beautiful Portugal landmarks, dating back to the times of the Roman Empire, as it can add a final touch to the unforgettable impression of Lisbon. In 1147 a chapel was built in honor of St. Gens, the hermit, who was one of the first bishops of Lisbon. In the same place, he suffered martyrdom, after which he was canonized. 

A bit later the Augustinian monks installed the marble chair of St. Gens in the chapel. There is an interesting legend that highly recommends pregnant women to come here. It says that If a woman who is waiting for the baby sits on this chair, she can give birth easily and without complications. Even the wife of King João V of Portugal, Donna Maria Anna of Austria, followed this advice when she was pregnant with the heir to the throne. This tradition is carefully kept to this day

fields.name: Gulbenkian Museum
fields.page_description: This museum in Lisbon demonstrates an exquisite collection of art, dedicated to various cultures and periods. Get a diverse artistic experience, exploring ancient artifacts and modern masterpieces.
fields.introduction_title: The Calouste Gulbenkian Museum: One of the Most Significant Lisbon Art Exhibitions
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The Calouste Gulbenkian Museum is an art exhibition in Lisbon with a solid collection of European fine art and ancient artworks. It was opened on October 2, 1969, by Calouste Gulbenkian, an Armenian billionaire who donated a priceless collection of works of art from Europe, Asia, and Africa to the Portuguese capital.

While the museum is a cultural attraction, the surrounding park is a bright example of a landscape design with numerous rest zones. The visit here is a great idea for the vacation of all family members. For the Portuguese, the museum art collection in Lisbon is a source of pride, and for tourists, it is a must-see place for day trips from Lisbon to explore the city and country.

The exhibits are brilliant, and each of them deserves special attention. The list of names of artists whose works are exhibited in the museum is overwhelming. In addition to paintings, the Gulbenkian Museum in Lisbon also presents decorative items and sculptures from Egypt, Persia, and Greece. 

Here are available rare ancient books and antique furniture from France. The museum complex is on the list of the World's most famous and richest museums. There are also many Art Deco items in the museum: jewelry, a collection of glass, and decorative objects
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The collection of exhibits includes more than 6 thousand items with about one thousand on display. The focus of attention is the Lalique part of the collection dating to the 11th-20th centuries. Additionally, there are many medieval items. The collection of medieval books and manuscripts occupies a separate room.

But most of the visitors come here to see the paintings, and it’s the main reason why the museum is one of the brightest cultural attractions of Lisbon. Original canvases by Rembrandt, Rubens, and Van Eyck are presented here. A big part of the collection is made of the paintings of English artists, such as Turner and Gainsborough. Additionally, there is a large collection of impressionists, including paintings by Claude Monet, Renoir, and Degas. And besides the above, there is a huge number of less famous, but no less talented painters.

The museum has a large collection of antique furniture and an even larger collection of gold and silver objects: jewelry, decorative, and for home use. A special place is occupied by the collection of Armenian and Middle Eastern art. 

Some tourists come to the Museu Calouste Gulbenkian to visit one of the Lisbon cultural activities held here. After the visit, it’s highly recommended to walk through the garden which is a well-maintained recreation area with numerous sculptures.

fields.name: Vasco da Gama Bridge
fields.page_description: Vasco da Gama Bridge in Lisbon was opened in 1996 and nowadays is one of the most impressive landmarks of the Portuguese capital. The architectural structure is a striking combination of functionality with beauty and grace.
fields.introduction_title: Vasco da Gama Bridge: One of The Most Significant Landmarks in Lisbon
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Vasco da Gama Bridge in Lisbon was opened in 1996 and nowadays is one of the most impressive landmarks of the Portuguese capital. The architectural structure is a striking combination of functionality with beauty and grace. The capacity of the regular six-lane highway is up to 52,000 vehicles. As for the periods when the traffic load increases several times, there are 2 more additional lanes.

The length of the bridge is 17.2 km and the width is 30 meters. It was built to reduce traffic on Lisbon's first bridge, known as the 25 April Bridge. The project was carried out after taking into account a set of factors that could affect the performance, safety, and service life of the structure, such as the characteristics of the bottom topography and the landscapes of the northern and southern banks of the Tagus, environmental, and aesthetic aspects. 

The bridge was created by the French engineer Michel Virlojo. He managed to carry out an amazing project, taking into account all the nuances of safe construction, fitting it perfectly into the landscape, and keeping the ecological balance of the environment
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The Vasco da Gama Bridge in Lisbon is recognized as a real miracle of modern engineering. It makes a lasting impression on the audience, and it should be seen within Lisbon tours to create a full impression of the city. It's definitely the most stunning among Portuguese bridges. To see the bridge in all its beauty it's recommended to have a look from the embankment, from the Park of Nations, from the cable car cabins. Those who are keen on active sports can have a look from a paraglider. Wonderful photos and videos against the backdrop of the gigantic structure are guaranteed.

For two decades, it occupied first place in the ranking of the longest bridges in Europe. When entering, the opposite side is not visible, creating the illusion of infinity. That part of the structure which passes over the Park of Nations is one of the most striking attractions of the capital of Portugal. 

Bridge design and architecture make a special impression at night as soft luminous points are reflected in the water. The bridge is modern and safe, but the route is often used by local street racers, who cause large-scale car accidents. 

The entrance on the bridge is chargeable because the funds for the construction of this attraction were allocated by the Lusoponte consortium, which received a 40-year concession. However, a high-speed trip on a broadband highway and wonderful views are worth spending a certain amount of money and time on traveling across the bridge

fields.name: Chiado
fields.page_description: Chiado is a vibrant and upscale neighborhood in central Lisbon. It's well-known for its trendy shops, theaters, and cafes. Tourists are attracted to this neighborhood because it combines a lively atmosphere with historical charm.
fields.introduction_title: Chiado: One of The Most Vibrant Districts in Lisbon
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
Chiado is one of the oldest neighborhoods in the Portuguese capital, located right in its heart, between Bairro Alto and the center of Baixa Pombalina.

The appearance of the name of the district goes back to the 16th century. Some say that the area got its name after the poet António Ribeiro (1520-1591), whose statue can be seen in the main square. According to another version, the name was given in honor of Gaspar Dias, who ran a pub on Rua Paiva Andrade. Both had the nickname “Shiado”, which can be translated as “sneaky”.

This elegant district is an intellectual center of Lisbon, which houses numerous theaters, antique shops, and bookstores. In the 19th century, this district was especially popular among writers who formed an unforgettable Bohemian atmosphere. It's highly recommended to walk through the main shopping street of Chiado, Rua Garett, which is full of antique shops. The Basilica of Nossa Senhora dos Martires, built in 1147, is the historical and architectural landmark of the street. Even though most of the buildings in Chiado are dated back to the 18th century, they were destroyed in a fire in 1988.

The renovation was carried out by the Portuguese architect Alvaro Siza Vieira. As a result of his work a unique architectural ensemble of new and restored buildings was created.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
For example, in old times Chiado was used as the shortcut of the city to the surrounding farms and monasteries. The gates of the ancient fortress walls were built in the 14th century by order of King Fernando in the square of two churches, Our Lady of Loreto and Our Lady of the Incarnation. Nowadays, after the restoration, the fragments of these walls are the elements of some city buildings. 

The boundaries of the area are not clear as there are no walls or strict divisions by the streets. But it is quite clear that the Chiado area includes Largo do Carmo Square, Rua Garrett Street with the Church of the Martyrs, Camoes, and the Largo Trindade Coelho squares with the Church of Saint Roca. 

Chiado is rich not only in historical landmarks but also in culture. Not far from the theater district, there is another attraction, the Chiado Museum with rare exhibitions which definitely deserve attention. 

The best idea to explore the area is on foot as it's relatively small. While walking, the visitors should visit local shops, some of which are at least a hundred years old, and then have a rest in one of the fancy cafes to feel the atmosphere of the place.

If you stay here overnight, go to the neighboring Upper District (Bairro Alto). This area, with small streets full of bars and restaurants for every taste, is one of the most popular and crowded places in the city at night.

fields.name: The Quake Museum
fields.page_description: The Quake Museum is an interactive exhibition where visitors can explore the science of earthquakes and their impacts on Portugal in 1755. This immersive simulator and educational center is dedicated to natural disasters.
fields.introduction_title: The Quake Museum: An Interactive Earthquake Center
fields.introduction_text_above_slider:
The Quake Museum is a new interactive attraction for the whole family in Lisbon, founded by Mayor Carlos Moidas. It is a space with a total area of 1,800 square meters with numerous options for entertainment. The implementation of the project cost 8 million euros, and today everyone has the opportunity to feel the atmosphere of the 1755 earthquake.

This thematic experience offers many options for maximum immersion in the atmosphere of 18th-century Lisbon. The immersive program includes several rooms where visitors can experience the full spectrum of the earthquake. The creators managed to successfully combine history, science, and emotions, making the attraction interesting for visitors of all ages.

A high level of interactivity is reached by using new technologies to transport visitors back to the day when Lisbon suffered from an earthquake. At that time it was the fourth largest city in the world, but natural disasters radically changed the situation.
fields.introduction_text_below_slider:
The attraction is a unique chance to make a journey in a time machine, discovering the mysteries of the city that was lost, but then rebuilt in all its beauty the way we know it today. The interactive displays demonstrate the seismic activity while the visitors are walking by the streets of old Lisbon.

Through a scientific and historical perspective, the visitors will know everything about the earthquake's effects in Lisbon, same as the facts about the social leaders and villains who played key roles in the reconstruction. You'll also experience an earthquake in a Quake simulator, a room built using the latest technology to provide a shaky but safe experience.

But the main part of the journey is the simulator. The unique room was created to let the visitors feel the experience of a real earthquake, being safe and protected at the same time.

The Lisbon Earthquake Museum is an invitation to discover the wonders and horrors of that era and watch the drama unfold before your eyes.

fields.question: What other attractions are accessible near St. George's Castle?
fields.answer: The visit to the castle can be combined with other things to see in Lisbon city, such as the historic neighborhood of Alfama, the Fado Museum, and the Cathedral. Visitors can also enjoy scenic walks along the Tagus River or explore the vibrant markets and cafes in the surrounding area.

fields.question: Is it allowed to take photos in St. George's Castle?
fields.answer: Photography for personal use is allowed inside St. George's Castle, but in some areas, there are guidelines regarding photography, so it's recommended to be respectful to them.

fields.question: Can visitors bring their own food and drinks to St. George's Castle?
fields.answer: Yes, as there are no restrictions, but alcohol is not allowed as it's the object of high historical value. The main rule is to act respectfully to medieval Lisbon sites, not litter.

fields.question: Are there any tram 28 travel tips, especially during peak time?
fields.answer: The best time for the tram 28 ride is early in the morning, as this way you can avoid crowds. The tram is very full on the weekends, so it's also recommended to get a ride on a weekday.

fields.question: Are there audio guides on Tram 28 to learn about the history of the route?
fields.answer: As it's an active tram route, there are no onboard audio guides. People can easily access all the important information about the historical heritage of Lisbon and its landmarks on the Internet. But the best way is to get this experience with a guide in terms of a one-day tour of Lisbon.

fields.question: Are there official stops along the Tram 28 route to hop on and off to explore the most interesting things to visit in Lisbon?
fields.answer: Yes, the fixed stops allow the passengers to hop off and explore key points of interest. But keep in mind that the tram does not arrive frequently, so you may have to wait up to 40 minutes for the next one.

fields.question: Are there any specific dress code requirements for visiting the Jerónimos Monastery?
fields.answer: There is no strict dress code, but it's advisable to discover Lisbon’s Heritage, dressing modestly, and covering shoulders and knees as a sign of respect for the religious site.

fields.question: Is photography allowed inside the Jerónimos Monastery, and are there any restrictions?
fields.answer: Yes, photography is allowed in most Portuguese monasteries, but some sections may have restrictions. It's advisable to pay attention to the signs or ask the staff for guidance.

fields.question: Are there any special events in the excursion program around the monastery?
fields.answer: Yes, the Jerónimos Monastery hosts cultural events, concerts, and exhibitions. But it's not regular, so it's advisable to check the information before planning the visit.

fields.question: Is there an optimal time to visit Alfama?
fields.answer: Consider visiting in the late afternoon or evening to experience Alfama Lisbon nightlife and catch live Fado performances. The district is on the list of must-see things in Lisbon, which truly comes alive at the sunset.

fields.question: Where can tourists enjoy traditional Portuguese cuisine in Alfama?
fields.answer: The best restaurants in Alfama with panoramic views open their doors to all the volunteers. Try tapas, seafood, and local wines, and enjoy the sunset. Most of the spots provide an authentic taste of Portuguese culinary delights.

fields.question: Is there a walking tour from Lisbon Portugal to Alfama with a guide?
fields.answer: Yes, there are walking tours in Lisbon with experienced guides. Deep insights into the history, architecture, and culture of this fascinating district are guaranteed.

fields.question: What is the best time of day to see Praca do Comercio architecture?
fields.answer: For quiet exploration without a crowd of tourists, the best option is early morning. For sunset views in the lively atmosphere, it's better to come to the square in the evening.

fields.question: How to get to Praça do Comércio by public transportation?
fields.answer: There are many options for public transport, such as tram, bus, or metro. The Baisha-Chiado metro station is within walking distance, or you can simply walk from other city center attractions, such as Alfama and Bairro Alto.

fields.question: What are the must-see attractions within Praça do Comércio?
fields.answer: In the center of attention is Arco da Rua Augusta with panoramic views of the square and the Tagus River. Additionally, pay attention to the Commerce Square Statue and Ribeira Palace. To get deeper insights into Praca do Comercio history, it's recommended to come here with a local guide.

fields.question: Is there a parking area near Belem Tower?
fields.answer: Near Belem Tower is available parking, but during peak tourist season it can be difficult to find a free place. It's recommended to come early in the morning and avoid weekends.

fields.question: What is the best way to visit Belem Tower to avoid crowds?
fields.answer: Morning time during weekdays is generally more quiet at Belem Tower. To make the most of your visit it's recommended to arrive early in the morning and become one of the first visitors. Belem Tower sunset views also deserve attention.

fields.question: Is the top of Belem Tower open for visitors?
fields.answer: Yes, it's one of must see things in Lisbon, available for visitors to climb to the top of Belem Tower to enjoy stunning views of the city and the peaceful landscape of the Tagus River. As there are narrow staircases, the top is not available for wheelchairs.

fields.question: Is it allowed to take photos inside the Azulejos Museum?
fields.answer: Yes, it's allowed to take photos for personal use inside the museum. At the same time, flash is forbidden as it may influence the safety of the artifacts. In case of any individual request, such as a professional photo session, it's required to ask for permission beforehand.

fields.question: Is it forbidden to touch the azulejos exhibits at the museum?
fields.answer: The visitors are kindly requested not to touch or handle the examples to ensure the preservation of the exhibits. For the safety of tiles are created special conditions to guarantee safety.

fields.question: Are there gift shops to buy replicas of azulejos at the Azulejos Museum?
fields.answer: Yes, there are souvenir shops for any request. Most of them offer souvenirs with replicas, books, and other products related to the tile art and culture.

fields.question: How to get to Senhora do Monte Viewpoint from the center of Lisbon?
fields.answer: You can reach Senhora do Monte Viewpoint by taking Tram 28. One more way, if you're in the Graça neighborhood, is to go on foot. On average it takes about 15-20 minutes.

fields.question: Is there comfortable wheelchair access to Senhora do Monte Viewpoint?
fields.answer: There are no restrictions on the viewpoint itself and it's accessible. On the other hand, the ascent to reach it involves steep streets and stairs, which may create challenges for wheelchair users.

fields.question: Are there any additional facilities available at Senhora do Monte Viewpoint?
fields.answer: Yes, there are special areas, such as benches and shaded areas, where the visitors can rest, calmly enjoying the view. Also, there are numerous nearby cafes and restaurants for refreshments.

fields.question: What are the most significant artworks at the Gulbenkian Museum?
fields.answer: The collection of the Gulbenkian Museum is huge, and the list includes Rembrandt, Rubens, and Monet. The museum houses paintings, sculptures, and decorative arts from different periods, providing insights into European art history. These artworks deserve the attention of the true art connoisseurs.

fields.question: Can visitors buy souvenirs or replicas of artworks from the Museum Gift Shop?
fields.answer: Yes, there is an official gift shop with a wide variety of unique and locally crafted souvenirs, replicas, and special literature. All the volunteers have the opportunity to take a piece of art home. There are also replicas of modern and contemporary artworks, that contrast with the museum's historical collections.

fields.answer: No, Vasco da Gama Bridge is closed for pedestrians for safety reasons. But for the comfort of tourists and locals, there are designated areas for leisure activities and cycling paths nearby, perfectly located to enjoy the scenic views of the bridge.

fields.question: What are the best options to try local cuisine in Chiado?
fields.answer: Chiado is a great place to take a journey into Portuguese cuisine. Along Rua Garrett are located numerous cafes and restaurants. The visitors can choose any of them and savor traditional Portuguese dishes.

fields.question: What about shopping and buying souvenirs in Chiado?
fields.answer: Chiado is a great place for shopping as here can be found everything from designer boutiques along the main street to local shops with handcrafted items, perfect for gifts.

fields.question: Is Chiado a good choice to stay overnight and feel the nightlife of Lisbon?
fields.answer: Chiado is one of the districts, popular among visitors with a vibrant nightlife scene. There are numerous trendy bars and cozy taverns. It's a place where there is something for everyone to enjoy.

fields.question: Is the Quake Museum a good idea for a visit for the whole family?
fields.answer: Yes, the museum is an exciting educational platform for a fun experience for visitors of all ages with informative and entertaining exhibits.

fields.question: Is it possible to get a guided tour of the Quake Museum?
fields.answer: Yes, there are available guided tours, created by professional staff members. They present the science of earthquakes with the history of seismic events in Portugal, creating an interactive space for an immersive experience.

fields.question: How to get to the Quake Museum in Lisbon?
fields.answer: As the museum is located right in the center of Lisbon, it's easily accessible by public transportation. Those who come by car can have access to the parking facilities nearby.

fields.name: Lisbon
fields.page_description: Discover the best Lisbon tours, attractions, and experiences to make the most of your trip. Explore the beauty and culture of Lisbon with our top recommendations.
fields.main_subtitle: The capital of Portugal, one of the most vibrant and charismatic cities in Western Europe.
fields.introduction_subtitle: The capital of Portugal is one of the oldest cities in Europe, filled with countless historical, architectural, and cultural attractions. Located on the picturesque banks of the Tagus River, Lisbon is a perfect spot to start the journey through Portugal.
fields.introduction_text:
Lisbon is a perfect blend of elegant palaces, luxurious squares, majestic cathedrals, historical museums, and monuments with narrow cozy pretty streets and neat houses decorated with traditional Portuguese Azulejo tiles. You can start your walk around the city from the Ribeira market, where you can try delicacies from all over the country at once. Continue to Commerce Square and then explore the Lisbon Cathedral.

Climb a little higher, walk to the archaeological museum and the Carmo Convent, and from there go to the Santa Justa elevator with a panoramic view at the top.

In the center, you can take the old tram 28, get off at the very top of the Basilica of Estrela, and explore it and the cozy park next door. Then get to the Castle of St. George, and explore its towers and fortress walls, halls, and museums.

The number of sightseeing is incredible, many of them are on the UNESCO list, so a professional guide to the main places is the best solution to dive into the culture.
fields.short_introduction_text: The capital of Portugal is one of the oldest cities in Europe, filled with countless historical, architectural, and cultural attractions. Located on the picturesque banks of the Tagus River, Lisbon is a perfect spot to start the journey through Portugal.
fields.when_to_visit_text:
The weather conditions in Portugal can be called warm and sunny, and in winter it's also quite comfortable here. The exact weather is always up to the Lisbon weather forecast, but there is still some common information. The best period to travel to Lisbon is considered to be May - October. 

In spring, the weather will delight with comfortable temperatures of +17...+24 and the city will not yet be filled with tourists. The peak tourist season is in the summer period, when the temperature may reach +28, and during this time excursion holidays can be combined with a sea holiday. In autumn, the weather is still warm and sunny, +18...+25, so the trip will be much more comfortable. In winter the temperature stays within +10-15, so in the daytime, it is perfect for trips around Portugal.
fields.getting_around_text:
For tourists who don't rent a car, there is an efficient Lisbon public transportation system. It's easy to get around by bus, tram, and the metro. 

The first tip for a comfortable stay in Lisbon is a Lisboa Card. It provides unlimited access to public transportation and special discounts for visiting attractions, but this solution is good for long-term stay. As for one-time trips on public transport, it's possible to pay in cash directly to the driver. The cost of the trip depends on the type of transport. For a bus trip, it's 1.85€, 2.90€ for a tram, 3.70€ for funiculars, and €5.15 for both ways on Santa Justa. 

A well-thought-out transport system helps to enjoy Lisbon as a dynamic, open-air city that boasts stunning scenery, cobbled streets, and plenty of historical attractions and activities.
fields.travel_tips_text:
You can get an unforgettable experience while traveling in Lisbon if you consider a few simple tips:

1. How to make the first trip to Lisbon unforgettable?

Lisbon is a destination, which offers all types of activities for tourists. To make your experience more vivid, admire the city from the observation deck. The view of Lisbon from above is impressive and enchanting. All the beauty of the city appears before the viewer: the Tagus River, ships sailing along it, the ocean, bridges, churches, and houses. If you're out of time, the best option to see all the main sights and attractions is to choose a one-day tour in Lisbon. And don't forget to try Portuguese wines as the country is famous for its vineyards. Red and white wines from the region are distinguished by high taste qualities.

2. What is a list of hidden treasures of Lisbon?

It may not be enough to visit the most popular tourist attractions to create a full impression of Lisbon. If you're interested in non-tourist places, Lisbon is extremely rich in such locations. For the first adventure, pay attention to the underground Roman galleries. One more place is Reservoir Mahe d'Agua Amoreiras. The reservoir, which received the title of Queen of Water, was built to collect flows from the main Lisbon aqueduct. And if you have time, visit the National Museum of Costume and Fashion. This museum displays male, female, and children's clothing that was considered fashionable from the 17th to the mid-20th century. To avoid crowds but still see Lisbon from the top, visit Miradouro Santa Catarina and Miradouro São Pedro de Alcântara viewpoints. It's highly recommended to choose tours with experienced local guides to see Lisbon from an unknown side.

3. What dishes are the must-try in Lisbon?

What to eat in the city, located by the ocean? Of course, the focus of attention is a variety of seafood dishes in the best restaurants in Lisbon: baked octopus, shrimp, oysters, lobsters, mussels, and fish. The “bacalhau”, for example, Pastéis de bacalhau (cod croquettes) or Bacalhau à bras (stewed cod with potatoes, onions, and eggs), is a very famous local Portuguese dish, originally from Lisbon. The portions are large, so you can share it for 2 people. And be sure to leave a place for dessert! The famous Paste de Belem (or Pastel de Nata) cakes are the number one dessert in Portugal.

fields.name: Porto
fields.page_description: Discover the best Porto tours, attractions, and experiences to make the most of your trip. Explore the beauty and culture of Porto with our top recommendations.
fields.main_subtitle: Charming Old Town with Iconic Bridges, Historic Port Wine Cellars, and Vibrant Culture.
fields.introduction_subtitle: Porto, the second largest city of Portugal and the capital of port wine is a perfect blend of the classic look with a modern atmosphere.
fields.introduction_text:
The city of Porto is one of the largest in Portugal. It received the name Porto Calais in honor of the two Roman tribes Portus and Calais, which in ancient times lived on different banks of the Douro River. Despite the centuries-old rivalry with Lisbon, Porto is considered to be the real capital of Portugal in the north. The city is located on Pena Ventosa Hill near the Atlantic Ocean, boasting its beauty and an impressive number of attractions. The historical center of it has been preserved to this day in its original form. Since 1996, the city has been included in the UNESCO World Heritage List. 

In the 11th century, the Arabs were expelled from here, and Porto became a strategic point of the region. It was also the largest port, maintaining connections with England, Flanders, and the cities of the Hanseatic League. The future Henry the Navigator was born here.

The architecture of Porto is not as rich in palaces and cathedrals as Lisbon. At the same time, Porto tourist attractions are presented by monumental Baroque buildings, tiled churches, old factories, colorful roofs on gray stone buildings, trendy bars, informal shops, hidden picturesque streets, art venues, and contemporary art museums.

You can start your walk around the city from Avenida dos Aliados, where mansions from the late 19th and early 20th centuries have been preserved. Also here you can visit a bright example of Porto historical architecture - the Gothic Church of São Francisco, dating back to the 12th century. The cathedral served as a defensive structure along with the city walls. Nowadays it's open for visitors, showing the exquisite interior, bright frescoes, and stained glass windows.

The Clérigos Tower is one of the symbols of Porto, and also the tallest in the country (75 m). Previously, it served as a landmark for merchant ships entering the port. Today everyone can go up to the observation deck with a beautiful view of the entire city.

The Ribeira area with its small colorful houses on the hill is also a must-see. It’s good to walk along the narrow winding streets in any weather, enjoying the views and trying the cuisine in local cafes. And then you can make a trip on a ship or boat along the river with the colorful embankment of Cais de Ribeira.

Guimarães Castle is one of the most impressive buildings not only in the area around Porto but in all of Portugal. 4 towers, several gates, and a wooden bridge have survived to this day.

In your free time, take a stroll through the Porto Botanical Garden, the oldest in the country. It is divided into 3 parts: ponds with aquatic plants, flower beds, and greenhouses with tropical vegetation. Don't miss Porto art galleries and photography spots to make your experience of the city more complete. 

Among the museums, it is worth highlighting the Tram Museum, the exhibits of which are preserved in excellent condition. One more great place for family weekends: Crystal Palace Park with numerous playgrounds and areas for leisure activities. The park is decorated with all kinds of sculptures and installations made in modern and antique styles. Sports competitions, concerts, and other interesting cultural events for children and adults are regularly held here. The main entertainment for small visitors is feeding the peacocks, which stroll imposingly right across the lawns.

Modern Porto and its surroundings are developing dynamically. Nowadays it's one of the country's largest ports, and its residents are known for their patriotism and strive to emerge from the shadows of the capital's inhabitants.
fields.short_introduction_text: The second largest city of Portugal and the capital of port wine is a perfect blend of the classic look with a modern atmosphere. Being a traditional port city, Porto is the perfect blend of old-world charm and modern vibrancy.
fields.when_to_visit_text:
The best time to visit Porto in Portugal is in spring or early autumn months, like April, May, September, or October. This time, you can enjoy pleasant weather ideal for strolling along the picturesque streets, exploring its historic landmarks, and indulging in its renowned culinary scene.

Unlike Lisbon, Porto rarely gets very hot, and usually, it's a few degrees cooler here. The coldest months in Porto are December, January, and February, with temperatures averaging around 5°C to 14°C, but the city still looks amazing and you can enjoy slow walks by its historic streets and riverside views.

On the other hand, the hottest months are July and August, when temperatures can rise from 25°C to 30°C with high humidity. However, with its coastal location, you might find relief from the heat with a refreshing breeze off the Atlantic Ocean. And don't forget to check the Porto weather forecast before you go out.
fields.getting_around_text:
Porto has an efficient public transport system, which includes buses, trams, and the metro. The Andante Tour card is the perfect choice for those who don't want to spend time on the search for every type of transport. It comes in two types: 7 euros/24 hours, 15 euros/72 hours. It gives you the right to an unlimited number of trips on STCP city buses, the metro, the funicular, and the train.

Walking is ideal for exploring the compact city center, while iconic tram line 1 offers scenic rides along the waterfront. For more comfortable travel there are taxi services that provide convenient options. In warm periods there is one more popular option - cycling. 

Whether by foot, public transport, Porto river cruise, or bike, navigating Porto is convenient and enjoyable, allowing visitors to immerse themselves in its rich history and vibrant culture.
fields.travel_tips_text:
You can get an unforgettable experience while traveling in Porto if you consider a few simple Porto travel tips:

1. How to make the first trip to Porto unforgettable?

Porto, Portugal's second largest city and the country's northern capital, is a unique combination of historical heritage and modern charm. A professional guide will help you make your trip unforgettable, skillfully showing the beauty of the city combined with its modern life.

There are many attractions here, including a picturesque river, opportunities to visit the ocean, and beautiful churches, some of which are very ancient. Due to the compactness of the city, all attractions are close to each other, which makes walking around Porto especially convenient. This is a magnificent and exciting place that will forever leave a vivid impression in your hearts.

2. What is a list of hidden treasures of Porto?

Do you want to appreciate the beauty of all the outstanding sights of Porto at once? Then, pay attention to the Porto off the beaten path routes. Take a walk along the Ponte de Dom Luis I bridge. There are many bridges in the city, and this one is not the most hidden, but only a few know that it offers a wonderful view of the city. This gorgeous free “observation deck” is visited not only by dedicated tourists but also by professional photographers.

An equally attractive way to appreciate the panorama of the city is to go on a helicopter ride. 

3. What dishes are the must-try in Porto?

Porto is one of Europe's most exciting food destinations, with its hearty traditional seafood, and pork dishes such as tripas à moda do Porto, strong influences from the spices of the Age of Discovery.

Petiscarias are Portuguese-style tapas bars that offer small snacks to accompany your drinks. Try squid, olives, cheese, octopus salad, and Portuguese sausages such as alheira.

The most popular local cuisine in Porto is francesinha: a tower of generous slices of bread topped with ham, sausage, cheese, and sometimes a fried egg, doused in a spicy tomato sauce.

fields.name: Sintra
fields.page_description: Discover the best Sintra tours, attractions, and experiences to make the most of your trip. Explore the beauty and culture of Sintra with our top recommendations.
fields.main_subtitle: Magical Place with Fairytale Palaces, Lush Gardens, and Enchanting Landscapes.
fields.introduction_subtitle: Sintra is an ancient Portuguese city with a magical atmosphere and rich history.
fields.introduction_text:
Sintra is located near the capital of Portugal, east of the Sierra de Sintra mountains that separate it from the Bay of Biscay, being a perfect destination for day trips from Lisbon. Sintra is known for its numerous castles, parks and gardens, green vineyards, narrow streets, rich villas, and picturesque views of the sea and mountains.

You can start the Sintra sightseeing tour with a walk around the city center. Here is located one of the most famous attractions and its main symbol, Sintra Pena Palace. Built in the 19th century, the palace is not only a Sintra UNESCO World Heritage object but is also considered one of the Seven Wonders of Portugal. Sometimes it is even called Disneyland for adults as the building seems to have been copied from a collection of fairy tales! Thanks to the bright paintings, numerous turrets, courtyards, and elaborate romantic architecture, the building looks like a toy.

The next must-visit spots are the Pena Gardens and the summit of Cruz Alta. Here you can simply walk, admiring the numerous statues, decorative pools, and elegant gazebos. Additionally, it is worth visiting the top of the Cruz Alta hill in the southern part of the park. Here, at an altitude of 529 meters above sea level, is the highest point of Sintra, from where Lisbon can be seen in good weather.

A 20-minute walk from the Pena Gardens is the medieval Sintra Moorish Castle, which was founded in the 10th century. Its powerful towers, parapets, and battlements will delight any fans of history. However, even if the Middle Ages are not the focus of your interest, you will probably enjoy the breathtaking views of the surrounding area. Sintra lives its own life below, and far on the horizon are seen the waters of the Atlantic Ocean.

Montserrat Manor is another famous object of Sintra cultural heritage and the second must-have palace in Sintra. The villa is decorated in a romantic style, attracting attention with the impeccable decoration of the interior rooms. No less charming is the luxurious park around the mansion with a lake in the middle, numerous springs, grottoes, and rare species of trees.

There is hardly a list of attractions that does not include Sintra Quinta da Regaleira. A huge mansion with a mystical 19th-century park in the Gothic style is rightfully considered the pearl of Sintra. The gardens of Quinta da Regaleira are full of symbolism and secret meanings, references to religion, alchemy, and Freemasonry. Quinta da Regaleira is full of unexpected finds and sudden discoveries. But undoubtedly the main attraction here is the Well of Dedication (Poço Iniciático).

The Well of Dedication is a spiral staircase that goes 27 meters deep. The staircase looks like a tower screwed into the ground and, thanks to this strange shape, is shrouded in many outlandish legends.

If you have free time in Sintra and want to see it from another angle, pay attention to the shoreline as here is located the incredibly popular Agrada beach, famous for its waves and the sports competitions that constantly take place here (including world-class ones). Among others should be mentioned large Grande Beach, the most beautiful beach in Portugal, Baby Ursa, Praia das Masanches, and Magoito. If you take the opportunity to go surfing, fishing, and other water activities in the clear water of the Atlantic Ocean and on the golden sands of local beaches, then Sintra will be a paradise for travelers. No big surprise, that this city is considered the main tourist destination of the so-called Portuguese Riviera.
fields.short_introduction_text: An ancient Portuguese city with a magical atmosphere and rich history, surrounded by lush greenery, Sintra showcases colorful castles with breathtaking panoramic views. Pena Palace, one of the well-known landmarks, is a must-visit attraction.
fields.when_to_visit_text:
The optimal time to explore Sintra in Portugal is during the spring or early autumn months when it's already warm, but still not too hot. Delightful weather perfect for discovering the rich cultural heritage of Portugal, and savoring its delectable cuisine, is guaranteed.

Unlike Lisbon, Sintra typically stays a bit cooler, with temperature usually a few degrees lower. The coldest months in Sintra are December, January, and February, with temperatures from 5°C to 14°C. 

The hottest months are July and August when temperatures can stay between 25°C to 30°C with high humidity a bit softened with refreshing breezes blowing in from the Atlantic Ocean. Be sure to keep an eye on the Sintra weather forecast to plan your perfect outdoor activities.
fields.getting_around_text:
Sintra transportation options are variable, so anybody can choose the best one. Taxi service is available at the train station or opposite the Sintra Vila post office. The one-way fare is approximately 10 EUR to the Pena Palace or 18 EUR to the Capuchin Monastery and back. On weekends and holidays, there is a 20% surcharge.

There is a regular bus (number 433) which runs from Portela Interface to San Pedro for 1€. Bus number 434 (circular bus route), which leaves from Sintra train station, will take you to Pena Palace. The ticket price is 5 EUR for all day.

For 12 EUR you can buy a Day Rover - a ticket valid on all Scotturb buses.

One more option is to get a bicycle as cycling in Sintra can be quite fun and interesting. You can rent it at Caminho do Castelo.

On weekends and holidays, there are a lot of cars in the city, and parking becomes a problem.
fields.travel_tips_text:
You can get an unforgettable experience while traveling in Sintra if you consider a few simple Sintra travel tips:

1. How to make the first trip to Sintra unforgettable?

Sintra is a place with a magical atmosphere, filled with fairy tales and romance, so visiting it is an unforgettable experience.

Architectural masterpieces can be found here at every step. The splendor of ancient castles coexists with modern amenities. Sintra boasts stylish restaurants and pleasant cafes, together with comfortable old-fashioned hotels. Give yourself the pleasure of enjoying the beauty, and then relax, sitting comfortably in one of the picturesque cafes. A professional guide would show the hidden treasures of Sintra, creating an unforgettable impression, so you'd like to return here again and again.

2. What is a list of Sintra hidden gems?

There is an attraction of Sintra within the territory of Montserrat, unknown for most of the tourists. These are the ruins of an ancient chapel.

The ruins are close to the entrance gate, but away from the main path. According to legend, the chapel was destroyed by the Great Lisbon Earthquake of 1755. Over the years, the trees around grew and completely swallowed up the ruins.

In reality, in 1855, Montserrat was bought from a Portuguese family by a wealthy English merchant, Sir Francis Cook. He was much into the artificial ruins and wanted to give it a more mystical aura. The chapel looks amazing, and nothing shows its man-made origin.

3. What dishes are the must-try in Sintra?

Sintra is a town lost in time, although it is not so far from Lisbon, the spirit of antiquity is felt everywhere, which means this is where you can try classic Portuguese dishes. Sintra local cuisine mainly consists of fish, seafood, cheese, and vegetables.

There are a lot of fish restaurants in Sintra, probably every establishment serves seafood, and this is not surprising, there are so many local seafood delicacies!

Traditional sweets of Sintra are the Queijadas de Sintra and Travesseiros. You will find them in any cafe (pastelaria) in the old town.
